  "final_answer": "Using low satisfaction as a proxy for high stress, there are \\textbf{8 students} who appear stressed despite relatively low study/AI-use time (defined here as \\(\\le 1.8\\) hours/day, average \\(1.06\\) hours).\n\nA few patterns stand out:\n- \\textbf{Grades may be a key factor}: 4 of the 8 saw \\emph{no change} in grades, and 1 had a \\emph{slight decline}. That suggests stress may come from feeling that effort is not translating into results.\n- \\textbf{Writing and research tasks} are common in this group (3 in writing, 2 in research), which may reflect deadline pressure, academic expectations, or frustration with task difficulty.\n- The group is evenly split between \\textbf{school and college} students (4 each), so this pattern is not limited to one education level.\n- The students are spread evenly across Lahore, Multan, Faisalabad, and Karachi, so there is no strong city-specific signal.\n- Most used ChatGPT or Gemini, but tool choice does not show a clear explanation on its own.\n\nOverall, the strongest likely explanation is not low study hours themselves, but rather \\textbf{low perceived payoff}: students may be spending limited time yet still feeling dissatisfied because their grades are not improving, or because the kind of work they are doing (especially writing/research) feels stressful or unproductive.",
